## 7. SYSTEMS MANAGER - SSM SESSION MANAGER

### Concept:
SSM Session Manager allows you to start a secure shell on your EC2 instances 
and on-premises servers WITHOUT SSH, bastion hosts, or SSH keys!

### Key Features:

✓ Start secure shell on EC2 and on-premises servers
✓ NO SSH access needed
✓ NO bastion hosts needed
✓ NO SSH keys needed
✓ NO port 22 needed (better security!)
✓ Supports Linux, macOS, and Windows
✓ Send session log data to S3 or CloudWatch Logs

### How It Works:

```
SESSION MANAGER ARCHITECTURE:

                              ┌────────────────────┐
                              │   EC2 Instance     │
                              │   (SSM Agent)      │
                              └─────────▲──────────┘
                                        │
                                Execute commands
                                        │
                              ┌─────────┴──────────┐
                              │  Session Manager   │
                              └─────────▲──────────┘
                                        │
                                IAM Permissions
                                        │
                              ┌─────────┴──────────┐
                              │       User         │
                              └────────────────────┘
```

### Why No SSH?

TRADITIONAL SSH:
- Open port 22 in security group
- Manage SSH keys
- Set up bastion hosts for private instances
- Security risk (exposed port)

SESSION MANAGER:
- No open ports needed!
- IAM authentication
- No key management
- Access private instances directly

### Security Benefits:

1. NO PORT 22
   - Smaller attack surface
   - No SSH-based attacks
   - No brute force attempts

2. IAM-BASED ACCESS
   - Centralized authentication
   - Fine-grained permissions
   - Easy to revoke access

3. AUDIT LOGGING
   - Every session logged
   - Commands recorded
   - S3 or CloudWatch storage

### Requirements:

EC2 INSTANCE:
- SSM Agent installed (pre-installed on Amazon Linux 2)
- IAM role with SSM permissions
- Outbound internet access (or VPC endpoint)

USER:
- IAM permissions for SSM
- AWS Console or CLI access

### Real-Life Example:
Think of Session Manager as a SECURE REMOTE DESKTOP without VPN:

TRADITIONAL APPROACH:
1. Set up VPN
2. Configure bastion host
3. Manage SSH keys
4. Open firewall ports
5. Finally connect!

SESSION MANAGER:
1. Have IAM permissions
2. Click "Start Session"
3. Connected!

### Daily Use Cases:

✓ Troubleshooting: Access instances for debugging
✓ Maintenance: Run commands, check logs
✓ Compliance: No exposed ports, full audit trail
✓ On-premises: Manage hybrid servers
✓ Emergency Access: No keys to lose

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

## 8. SYSTEMS MANAGER - RUN COMMAND

### Concept:
Run Command allows you to execute documents (scripts) or just run commands 
across multiple instances without SSH.

### Key Features:

✓ Execute documents (scripts) or commands
✓ Run across MULTIPLE instances (using resource groups)
✓ No need for SSH
✓ Command output to:
  - AWS Console
  - S3 bucket
  - CloudWatch Logs
✓ Notifications via SNS (In progress, Success, Failed)
✓ Integrated with IAM & CloudTrail
✓ Can be invoked using EventBridge

### Architecture:

```
RUN COMMAND FLOW:

Triggers:                          Output:
- AWS Console                      - Amazon S3
- AWS SDK           ┌─────────┐    - CloudWatch Logs
- Maintenance      │   Run    │    
  Windows    ───→  │ Command  │───→ Notifications:
- EventBridge      └────┬────┘     - Amazon SNS
                        │
                        │
              ┌─────────┴─────────┐
              │                   │
              ▼                   ▼
        EC2 Instance        EC2 Instance
        (SSM Agent)         (SSM Agent)
```

### Example Use Cases:

1. PATCH ALL INSTANCES
   - Select all instances with tag "Environment=Production"
   - Run: "yum update -y"
   - Results logged to S3
   - Notification when complete

2. COLLECT DIAGNOSTIC INFO
   - Run across all web servers
   - Execute diagnostic script
   - Collect results centrally

3. DEPLOY APPLICATION
   - Target: All instances in Auto Scaling Group
   - Run: Download and install new version
   - Verify: Check status

### SSM Documents:

WHAT ARE DOCUMENTS?
- Pre-defined or custom scripts
- AWS provides many built-in
- Create your own

BUILT-IN DOCUMENTS:
- AWS-RunShellScript (Linux)
- AWS-RunPowerShellScript (Windows)
- AWS-ConfigureAWSPackage
- AWS-UpdateSSMAgent
- Many more!

### Invocation Methods:

1. MANUAL (Console/CLI)
   - On-demand execution

2. EVENTBRIDGE
   - Event-triggered execution
   - "When instance launches, run setup script"

3. MAINTENANCE WINDOWS
   - Scheduled execution
   - "Every Sunday at 2 AM"

### Real-Life Example:
Think of Run Command as a REMOTE CONTROL for all your servers:

TRADITIONAL APPROACH:
1. SSH to server 1, run command
2. SSH to server 2, run command
3. SSH to server 3, run command
... (repeat 100 times)
4. Manually check each result
5. Hours of work!

RUN COMMAND:
1. Select all 100 servers (by tag)
2. Run command once
3. See all results in one place
4. Get notification when done
5. Minutes of work!

### Daily Use Cases:

✓ Patching: Update all instances
✓ Deployment: Deploy applications
✓ Configuration: Change settings
✓ Diagnostics: Collect information
✓ Compliance: Run compliance checks
✓ Automation: Event-driven responses

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

## 9. SYSTEMS MANAGER - PATCH MANAGER

### Concept:
Patch Manager automates the process of patching managed instances with OS 
updates, application updates, and security updates.

### Key Features:

✓ Automates patching of managed instances
✓ OS updates
✓ Application updates
✓ Security updates
✓ Supports EC2 instances AND on-premises servers
✓ Supports Linux, macOS, and Windows
✓ Patch on-demand OR on schedule (Maintenance Windows)
✓ Scan instances and generate compliance report

### Architecture:

```
PATCH MANAGER WORKFLOW:

Triggers:                         Execution:
- AWS Console      ┌──────────┐   
- AWS SDK         │ Run       │   run AWS-RunPatchBaseline
- Maintenance ───→│ Patch     │──────────────────────┐
  Windows         │ Baseline  │                      │
                  └──────────┘                       │
                                                     ▼
                                    ┌────────────────────────┐
                                    │     EC2 Instances      │
                                    │     (with SSM Agent)   │
                                    ├────────────────────────┤
                                    │ - Download patches     │
                                    │ - Install patches      │
                                    │ - Reboot if needed     │
                                    │ - Report compliance    │
                                    └────────────────────────┘
```

### Patch Baselines:

WHAT IS A PATCH BASELINE?
- Rules for which patches to apply
- Approval rules
- Exception lists

DEFAULT BASELINES:
- AWS provides default baselines per OS
- Can create custom baselines

CUSTOM BASELINE EXAMPLE:
- Auto-approve security patches after 7 days
- Auto-approve critical patches after 3 days
- Exclude specific patches

### Compliance Reports:

WHAT YOU SEE:
- Which instances are compliant
- Which patches are missing
- When last patched
- Failed patches

EXAMPLE REPORT:
```
Instance ID      Status     Missing Patches
i-123456789     Compliant  0
i-987654321     Non-Compl  3
i-555555555     Compliant  0
```

### Patching Methods:

1. ON-DEMAND
   - Patch now
   - Manual trigger

2. SCHEDULED (Maintenance Windows)
   - Patch every Sunday 2 AM
   - Automatic
   - No manual intervention

### Real-Life Example:
Think of Patch Manager as a FLEET MAINTENANCE SYSTEM:

TRADITIONAL PATCHING:
- IT admin logs into each server
- Checks for updates
- Installs updates
- Reboots if needed
- Documents what was done
- 100 servers = 100 manual sessions

PATCH MANAGER:
- Define patch baseline
- Schedule maintenance window
- Patch Manager handles everything
- Get compliance report
- 100 servers = 1 configuration

### Daily Use Cases:

✓ Security: Apply security patches automatically
✓ Compliance: Meet patching requirements
✓ Automation: Scheduled patching
✓ Reporting: Compliance dashboards
✓ Hybrid: Patch on-premises servers too

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

## 10. SYSTEMS MANAGER - MAINTENANCE WINDOWS

### Concept:
Maintenance Windows define a schedule for when to perform actions on your 
instances, such as OS patching, updating drivers, or installing software.

### Key Features:

✓ Define schedule for actions on instances
✓ Examples:
  - OS patching
  - Updating drivers
  - Installing software
  - Running scripts

### Maintenance Window Contains:

1. SCHEDULE
   - When to run
   - Cron expression or rate
   - Example: "Every Sunday at 2 AM"

2. DURATION
   - How long the window lasts
   - Example: "4 hours"

3. SET OF REGISTERED INSTANCES
   - Which instances to target
   - By tag, resource group, or specific IDs

4. SET OF REGISTERED TASKS
   - What to do
   - Run Command, Automation, Lambda, Step Functions

### Architecture:

```
MAINTENANCE WINDOW FLOW:

┌─────────────────┐     trigger every 24 hours     ┌─────────────┐
│   Maintenance   │ ─────────────────────────────→ │    Run      │
│    Windows      │              ⏰                 │   Command   │
└─────────────────┘                                └──────┬──────┘
                                                          │
                                                    update │
                                          ┌───────────────┼────────────────┐
                                          │               │                │
                                          ▼               ▼                ▼
                                    EC2 Instance    EC2 Instance     EC2 Instance
                                    (SSM Agent)     (SSM Agent)      (SSM Agent)
```

### Schedule Examples:

```
CRON EXPRESSIONS:

Every Sunday at 2 AM:
cron(0 2 ? * SUN *)

Every day at midnight:
cron(0 0 * * ? *)

First Monday of each month:
cron(0 0 ? * 2#1 *)

RATE EXPRESSIONS:

Every 24 hours:
rate(24 hours)

Every 7 days:
rate(7 days)
```

### Real-Life Example:
Think of Maintenance Windows as SCHEDULED CAR MAINTENANCE:

WITHOUT SCHEDULING:
- Remember to maintain each car
- Do maintenance during business hours
- Disrupts operations
- Inconsistent schedule

WITH MAINTENANCE WINDOWS:
- Scheduled maintenance every Sunday night
- No disruption to business
- Consistent and reliable
- Automated reminders and execution

### Task Types:

1. RUN COMMAND
   - Execute scripts
   - Run commands

2. AUTOMATION
   - Execute Automation runbooks
   - Complex workflows

3. AWS LAMBDA
   - Invoke Lambda functions
   - Custom logic

4. AWS STEP FUNCTIONS
   - Complex orchestration
   - Multi-step workflows

### Daily Use Cases:

✓ Patching: Scheduled OS updates
✓ Backups: Nightly backup scripts
✓ Cleanup: Remove old logs/files
✓ Updates: Application updates
✓ Compliance: Scheduled compliance checks

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

## 11. SYSTEMS MANAGER - AUTOMATION

### Concept:
SSM Automation simplifies common maintenance and deployment tasks of EC2 
instances and other AWS resources using Runbooks.

### Key Features:

✓ Simplifies maintenance and deployment tasks
✓ Examples:
  - Restart instances
  - Create an AMI
  - Create EBS snapshot
✓ Automation Runbook = SSM Documents that define actions
✓ Pre-defined OR custom runbooks

### Triggers:

1. MANUALLY
   - AWS Console
   - AWS CLI
   - AWS SDK

2. AMAZON EVENTBRIDGE
   - Event-driven automation
   - "When this happens, do that"

3. ON A SCHEDULE
   - Using Maintenance Windows

4. BY AWS CONFIG
   - For rules remediations
   - "When resource is non-compliant, fix it"

### Architecture:

```
AUTOMATION FLOW:

Triggers:
┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────┐  ┌─────────────┐  ┌──────────────┐
│ AWS Console  │  │ AWS SDK  │  │ Maintenance │  │ EventBridge  │
│              │  │          │  │   Windows   │  │              │
└──────┬───────┘  └────┬─────┘  └──────┬──────┘  └──────┬───────┘
       │               │               │                │
       └───────────────┴───────┬───────┴────────────────┘
                               │
                               ▼
                        execute automation
                     (AWS-RestartEC2Instance)
                               │
                               ▼
                        ┌─────────────┐
                        │  Runbooks   │
                        │ (automation │
                        │ documents)  │
                        └──────┬──────┘
                               │
                        ┌──────┴──────┐
                        │             │
                        ▼             ▼
                  EC2 Instances   AWS Resources
                                 (EBS, AMI, RDS)
```

### Built-in Runbooks:

AWS-RestartEC2Instance:
- Restart EC2 instance
- Handle state transitions

AWS-CreateImage:
- Create AMI from instance
- Automated backup

AWS-CreateSnapshot:
- Create EBS snapshot
- Point-in-time backup

AWS-UpdateLinuxAmi:
- Update AMI with latest patches
- AMI management

### Custom Runbooks:

CREATE YOUR OWN:
- Define steps
- Include conditionals
- Chain multiple actions
- Add error handling

EXAMPLE CUSTOM RUNBOOK:
1. Stop instance
2. Modify instance type
3. Start instance
4. Verify health
5. Notify via SNS

### Real-Life Example:
Think of Automation as your IT OPERATIONS PLAYBOOK:

WITHOUT AUTOMATION:
1. Someone notices issue
2. Logs into console
3. Figures out solution
4. Manually executes steps
5. Hopes they don't make mistakes
6. Documents what was done

WITH AUTOMATION:
1. Runbook already exists
2. Click "Execute" (or automatic trigger)
3. Automation follows steps perfectly
4. Results logged
5. Consistent every time

### Daily Use Cases:

✓ AMI Management: Create and update AMIs automatically
✓ Disaster Recovery: Automated failover procedures
✓ Cost Optimization: Stop/start instances on schedule
✓ Compliance: Remediate non-compliant resources
✓ Incident Response: Pre-defined response procedures
✓ Deployment: Automated deployment workflows

